<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPalmer2002" class="citation book cs1">Palmer, Grant H. (2002). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=c08mAQAAIAAJ"><i>An Insider's View of Mormon Origins</i></a>. Salt Lake City, UT: <a href="/wiki/Signature_Books" title="Signature Books">Signature Books</a>. pp.&#160;1–2. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781560851578" title="Special:BookSources/9781560851578"><bdi>9781560851578</bdi></a>. <q>Illustrations in the church magazine, the <i>Ensign</i>, depict the prophet studying the plates much like an archaeologist or classicist might.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=An+Insider%27s+View+of+Mormon+Origins&amp;rft.place=Salt+Lake+City%2C+UT&amp;rft.pages=1-2&amp;rft.pub=Signature+Books&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=9781560851578&amp;rft.aulast=Palmer&amp;rft.aufirst=Grant+H.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dc08mAQAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFTaves2014" class="citation journal cs1">Taves, Ann (2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://escholarship.org/uc/item/5s4591r8">"History and the Claims of Revelation: Joseph Smith and the Materialization of the Golden Plates"</a>. <i>Numen</i>. <b>61</b> (2/3): 182–207. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1163%2F15685276-12341315">10.1163/15685276-12341315</a> &#8211; via eScholarship. <q>Although modern LDS depictions of Smith translating the revelation often depict him looking at the plates, there is extensive insider testimony to the effect that he actually dictated his translation of the plates to scribes while looking at the 'interpreters'—the urim and thummim or his seer stone—positioned in a hat to block out the light.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Numen&amp;rft.atitle=History+and+the+Claims+of+Revelation%3A+Joseph+Smith+and+the+Materialization+of+the+Golden+Plates&amp;rft.volume=61&amp;rft.issue=2%2F3&amp;rft.pages=182-207&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1163%2F15685276-12341315&amp;rft.aulast=Taves&amp;rft.aufirst=Ann&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fescholarship.org%2Fuc%2Fitem%2F5s4591r8&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSweat2015" class="citation journal cs1">Sweat, Anthony (2015). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://rsc.byu.edu/vol-16-no-3-2015/role-art-teaching-latter-day-saint-history-doctrine">"The Role of Art in Teaching Latter-day Saint History and Doctrine"</a>. <i>Religious Educator</i>. <b>16</b>: 40–57. <q>For example, in each of the seventeen <i>Ensign</i> images, Joseph Smith is shown looking into open plates (not closed or wrapped or absent plates). . . . Most tellingly, none of the images ever printed in the history of the <i>Ensign</i> (or recent Church videos, such as <i>Joseph Smith, Prophet of the Restoration</i>) depict the translation process of the Book of Mormon as having taken place by placing a seer stone or the Nephite interpreters in a hat.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Religious+Educator&amp;rft.atitle=The+Role+of+Art+in+Teaching+Latter-day+Saint+History+and+Doctrine&amp;rft.volume=16&amp;rft.pages=40-57&amp;rft.date=2015&amp;rft.aulast=Sweat&amp;rft.aufirst=Anthony&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Frsc.byu.edu%2Fvol-16-no-3-2015%2Frole-art-teaching-latter-day-saint-history-doctrine&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKiJOAWNyAk">"Seer Stones and the Translation of the Book of Mormon"</a>. <i>Latter-day Saint History</i>. March 19, 2018. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/FKiJOAWNyAk">Archived</a> from the original on 2021-12-21<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">May 15,</span> 2021</span> &#8211; via YouTube. <q>For a long time, church art tended to depict the translation of the Book of Mormon as Joseph Smith and Oliver Cowdrey sitting around a table, sometimes with the gold plates on the table, but that's not really the best match for what we know about the translation process.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Latter-day+Saint+History&amp;rft.atitle=Seer+Stones+and+the+Translation+of+the+Book+of+Mormon&amp;rft.date=2018-03-19&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DFKiJOAWNyAk&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-27"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFGoble2017" class="citation web cs1">Goble, Clark (June 1, 2017). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.timesandseasons.org/harchive/2017/06/the-problem-of-mormon-art/index.html">"The Problem of Mormon Art"</a>. <i>Times &amp; Seasons</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">May 15,</span> 2021</span>. <q>People remember paintings that had Joseph with gold plates, indicating he read them. People didn't remember all the lessons that he translated them by looking at the Urim &amp; Thummim. . . . what they remembered was the misleading art.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Times+%26+Seasons&amp;rft.atitle=The+Problem+of+Mormon+Art&amp;rft.date=2017-06-01&amp;rft.aulast=Goble&amp;rft.aufirst=Clark&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.timesandseasons.org%2Fharchive%2F2017%2F06%2Fthe-problem-of-mormon-art%2Findex.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSmoot2015" class="citation web cs1">Smoot, Stephen Owen (April 28, 2015). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.plonialmonimormon.com/2015/04/book-notice-from-darkness-unto-light.html">"Book Notice: 'From Darkness unto Light: Joseph Smith's Translation and Publication of the Book of Mormon'<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span>"</a>. <i>Ploni Almoni</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">May 15,</span> 2021</span>. <q>The book includes a number of original pieces by Sweat depicting Joseph Smith's translation of the Book of Mormon by peering into a seer stone at the bottom of a hat.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Ploni+Almoni&amp;rft.atitle=Book+Notice%3A+%27From+Darkness+unto+Light%3A+Joseph+Smith%27s+Translation+and+Publication+of+the+Book+of+Mormon%27&amp;rft.date=2015-04-28&amp;rft.aulast=Smoot&amp;rft.aufirst=Stephen+Owen&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.plonialmonimormon.com%2F2015%2F04%2Fbook-notice-from-darkness-unto-light.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.fairlatterdaysaints.org/answers/Question:_What_Church_sources_discuss_either_the_use_of_the_seer_stone_or_the_stone_and_the_hat_as_part_of_the_Book_of_Mormon_translation_process%3F">"Question: What Church Sources Discuss Either the Use of the Seer Stone or the Stone and the Hat as Part of the Book of Mormon Translation Process?"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/FairMormon" class="mw-redirect" title="FairMormon">FAIR</a></i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">May 15,</span> 2021</span>. According to this timeline of church descriptions and depictions of the seer stone and hat in Smith's translation, illustrations in "the Church publication <i>From Darkness Unto Light: Joseph Smith's Translation and Publication of the Book of Mormon</i>, by Michael Hubbard Mackay and Gerrit J. Dirkmaat, Religious Studies Center, BYU, Deseret Book Company (May 11, 2015)" are the only church-produced visual depictions of Smith translating the golden plates by burying his face in the opening of a hat to examine seer stones placed inside.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=FAIR&amp;rft.atitle=Question%3A+What+Church+Sources+Discuss+Either+the+Use+of+the+Seer+Stone+or+the+Stone+and+the+Hat+as+Part+of+the+Book+of+Mormon+Translation+Process%3F&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fairlatterdaysaints.org%2Fanswers%2FQuestion%3A_What_Church_sources_discuss_either_the_use_of_the_seer_stone_or_the_stone_and_the_hat_as_part_of_the_Book_of_Mormon_translation_process%253F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormonism+and+history" class="Z3988"></span><span class="cs1-maint citation-comment"><code class="cs1-code">{{<a href="/wiki/Template:Cite_web" title="Template:Cite web">cite web</a>}}</code>:  CS1 maint: postscript (<a href="/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_postscript" title="Category:CS1 maint: postscript">link</a>)</span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Ronald_W._Walker" title="Ronald W. Walker">Ronald W. Walker</a>, David J. Whittaker, and <a href="/wiki/James_B._Allen_(historian)" title="James B. Allen (historian)">James B. Allen</a>, <i>Mormon History</i> (Urbana: <a href="/wiki/University_of_Illinois_Press" title="University of Illinois Press">University of Illinois Press</a>, 2001), 5.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Mormon History</i>, 8.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Ostling, 251. The church has always tried to retain control over the telling of its history.  When in 1853 <a href="/wiki/Orson_Pratt" title="Orson Pratt">Orson Pratt</a> published the memoirs of Joseph Smith's mother, <a href="/wiki/Lucy_Mack_Smith" title="Lucy Mack Smith">Lucy Mack Smith</a>, <a href="/wiki/Brigham_Young" title="Brigham Young">Brigham Young</a> "was unhappy with the book and ordered the printing destroyed." Ostling, 250. "It is not, for example, politically correct to suggest that Mormons, while victims, were not always innocent victims, or that though holiness may be an affront to the observer, ordinary Saintly holiness was not usually the cause of Mormon persecution."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Ostlings, 251.</span>
